properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 18 at 12:58PM CDT until April 18 at 1:30PM CDT by NWS Jackson MS
properties.description:
At 1257 PM CDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing a tornado
was located near Stanton, or 7 miles north of Natchez, moving
northeast at 55 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

This tornadic thunderstorm will remain over mainly rural areas of
northeastern Adams County.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 18 at 12:58PM CDT until April 18 at 3:00PM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Lake Charles has issued a

* Urban and Small Stream Flood Advisory for...
Lafayette Parish in south central Louisiana...
North central Vermilion Parish in southwestern Louisiana...
Northwestern St. Martin Parish in south central Louisiana...
South central St. Landry Parish in central Louisiana...

* Until 300 PM CDT.

* At 1257 PM CDT, Doppler radar indicated heavy rain due to
thunderstorms. This will cause urban and small stream flooding in
the advisory area.

* Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Lafayette, Scott, Breaux Bridge, Carencro, Leonville, Arnaudville,
Broussard, Youngsville, Sunset, Duson, Maurice, Grand Coteau,
Cankton, Indian Bayou, Ridge and Milton.

Additional rainfall of one to three inches is expected over the
area. This additional rain will result in minor flooding.
properties.instruction:
A Flood Advisory means river or stream flows are elevated, or ponding
of water in urban or other areas is occurring or is imminent.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 18 at 12:58PM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
At 1258 PM CDT, Doppler radar was tracking a strong thunderstorm near
Pecan Island, moving northeast at 60 mph.

Winds in excess of 40 mph will be possible with this storm.

Locations impacted include...
Abbeville, Kaplan, Intracoastal City, Forked Island, Pecan Island,
Erath, Delcambre, Meaux, Esther, Jefferson Island and Henry.
properties.instruction:
Torrential rainfall is also occurring with this storm, and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

properties.headline: Severe Thunderstorm Warning issued April 18 at 12:57PM CDT until April 18 at 1:30PM CDT by NWS New Orleans LA
properties.description:
At 1256 PM CDT, a severe thunderstorm was located near Albany, or 11
miles west of Hammond, moving northeast at 60 mph.

HAZARD...60 mph wind gusts and penny size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Expect damage to roofs, siding, and trees.

Locations impacted include...
Hammond, Amite, Amite City, Livingston, Independence, Roseland,
Albany, Springfield, Natalbany, Killian and Tickfaw.
properties.instruction:
A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 700 PM CDT for southeastern
Louisiana.

Remain alert for a possible tornado! Tornadoes can develop quickly
from severe thunderstorms. If you spot a tornado go at once into a
small central room in a sturdy structure.

For your protection move to an interior room on the lowest floor of a
building.

Continuous cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Move indoors immediately. Lightning is one of nature's leading
killers. Remember, if you can hear thunder, you are close enough to
be struck by lightning.

properties.description:

East Fork White River...Eel River...Flatrock River...Mill Creek...
Sugar Creek...Wabash River...White River...Wildcat Creek...Youngs
Creek...

.Lowland flooding has developed and will continue to develop across
many area rivers and streams including portions of the Wabash, White,
and East Fork White Rivers to end the week into the weekend.
Additional forecast rainfall of an inch and a half to over two inches
is expected across much of central Indiana through Saturday evening.
The bulk of the precipitation looks to fall today through Thursday
night, leading to the potential for more significant flooding.
The Flood Warning continues for
The White River at Newberry.
* until Friday April 26.
* At 12:30 PM Thursday the stage was 11.6 feet.
* Flood stage is 13.0 feet.
* Minor flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...Rise above flood stage by Saturday morning and continue
to rise to near 17.7 feet by late Monday night.  It will fall below
flood stage by Thursday April 25.
* At 18.0 feet...County Road 550 S in Greene County begins to flood.
County Road 600 W just north of the river flooded by possibly more
than a foot of water for a short distance in Mary Long Cutoff Area.
properties.instruction:
Precautionary/Preparedness Actions...

Motorists should never drive into flood water. Turn around and go
another way. Keep children away from flooded areas. Recreational and
agricultural interests should remain alert to changing river
conditions.

For detailed flood information go to weather.gov/ind on the web and
click on rivers and lakes.

properties.headline: Severe Thunderstorm Warning issued April 18 at 12:47PM CDT until April 18 at 1:30PM CDT by NWS New Orleans LA
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in New Orleans has issued a

* Severe Thunderstorm Warning for...
North central Ascension Parish in southeastern Louisiana...
Central Livingston Parish in southeastern Louisiana...
Southern Tangipahoa Parish in southeastern Louisiana...

* Until 130 PM CDT.

* At 1246 PM CDT, a severe thunderstorm was located near French
Settlement, or 13 miles northeast of Gonzales, moving northeast at
55 mph.

HAZARD...60 mph wind gusts.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Expect damage to roofs, siding, and trees.

* Locations impacted include...
Hammond, Amite, Ponchatoula, Amite City, Livingston, Independence,
Roseland, French Settlement, Albany, Port Vincent, Springfield,
Natalbany, Whitehall, Killian and Tickfaw.
properties.instruction:
A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 700 PM CDT for southeastern
Louisiana.

Remain alert for a possible tornado! Tornadoes can develop quickly
from severe thunderstorms. If you spot a tornado go at once into the
basement or small central room in a sturdy structure.

For your protection move to an interior room on the lowest floor of a
building.

Large hail and damaging winds and continuous cloud to ground
lightning is occurring with this storm. Move indoors immediately.
Lightning is one of nature's leading killers. Remember, if you can
hear thunder, you are close enough to be struck by lightning.

properties.description: Monitoring message only. Please disregard.
properties.instruction: Monitoring message only. Please disregard.

properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 18 at 12:45PM CDT until April 18 at 1:30PM CDT by NWS Jackson MS
properties.description:
At 1245 PM CDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing a tornado
was located near Ferriday, moving northeast at 35 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

This dangerous storm will be near...
Natchez and Vidalia around 1255 PM CDT.
Spokane around 100 PM CDT.

Other locations impacted by this tornadic thunderstorm include
Ridgecrest.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

the evening.

create hazardous conditions for small craft.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 18 at 12:36PM CDT by NWS New Orleans LA
properties.description:
At 1234 PM CDT, a strong thunderstorm was located near Port Allen,
moving north at 50 mph. This storm produced marble sized hail in
Iberville Parish.

Winds in excess of 30 mph and pea to marble size hail are possible
with this storm as it moves across Baton Rouge.

Locations impacted include...
Baton Rouge, Zachary, Baker, Port Allen, Oak Hills Place, Slaughter,
Westminster, Merrydale, Inniswold, Pride, Gardere, Brownfields,
Greenwell Spring and Baton Rouge Airport.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with this storm, and may cause
localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

This storm may intensify, so be certain to monitor local radio
stations and available television stations for additional information
and possible warnings from the National Weather Service.

A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 700 PM CDT for southeastern
Louisiana.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 18 at 1:25PM EDT until April 19 at 8:00PM EDT by NWS Burlington VT
properties.description:
Lake Champlain At Rouses Point
The National Weather Service in Burlington has issued a

* Flood Warning for
The Lake Champlain At Rouses Point.
* until Friday evening...Or until the warning is canceled.
* At  1:00 PM Thursday the stage was 100.1 feet.
* Flood stage is 100.0 feet.
* Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...The lake level will continue rising to near 100.2 feet
by this evening, and fall below flood stage after midnight Friday.
* Impact...At 100.0 feet...Water begins to enter some lake front
properties. Water also begins to threaten low lying roads, piers,
and docks. Wave action can compound flooding on windward facing
shorelines. Water will threaten the Burlington waterfront at
Perkins Pier and the King Street ferry dock.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...


Safety message...

Persons with interests in flood prone areas along Lake Champlain
should take action to protect their property. The combination of wind
and wave action will enhance flood effects on windward facing shores,
and may cause additional damage to shoreline roads and low lying
areas.

Obey all road closure signs, they are there for your safety. Do not
attempt to drive through flooded areas, most flood deaths occur in
automobiles. Turn around, don't drown!

Stay tuned to developments by listening to noaa weather radio, or by
visiting our web site at: weather.gov.

properties.headline: Flash Flood Watch issued April 18 at 11:51AM CDT until April 18 at 10:00PM CDT by NWS New Orleans LA
properties.description:
An unsettled and intense storm system will be moving through the
Lower Mississippi Valley region throughout the day. Strong to
severe thunderstorms are expected to develop with this system.
Efficient rainfall is anticipated to result with rain rates at
times high enough to produce flash flooding. The threat of
flooding rains will diminish after the passage of a strong cold
front later in the day from west to east.
The Flash Flood Watch continues for

* portions of southeast Louisiana and southern Mississippi,
including the following areas, in southeast Louisiana, East
Baton Rouge, East Feliciana, Livingston, Northern Tangipahoa,
Pointe Coupee, Southern Tangipahoa, St. Helena, St. Tammany,
Washington, West Baton Rouge, and West Feliciana. In southern
Mississippi, Amite, Pike, Walthall, and Wilkinson.

* until 10 PM CDT this evening

* Generally 2 to 3 inches of rainfall with locally higher
amounts to 5 inches possible. Rain rates at times may approach
4 inches per hour for several minutes.

* Impacts include rapid rises on area small streams and creeks.
Rapid ponding of water that may overwhelm local drainage
capacities due to excessive rain rates.
properties.instruction:
A Flash Flood Watch means that conditions may develop that lead
to flash flooding. Flash flooding is a very dangerous situation.

You should monitor later forecasts and be prepared to take action
should Flash Flood Warnings be issued.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 18 at 11:40AM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
At 1140 AM CDT, Doppler radar was tracking strong thunderstorms along
a line extending from 8 miles southwest of Walters to near Kaplan.
Movement was southeast at 30 mph.

Wind gusts up to 50 mph will be possible with these storms.

Locations impacted include...
Lafayette, New Iberia, Opelousas, Crowley, Abbeville, Catahoula,
Scott, Breaux Bridge, Rayne, Carencro, Ville Platte, St. Martinville,
Marksville, Kaplan, Church Point, Bunkie, Simmesport, Krotz Springs,
Leonville and Arnaudville.
properties.instruction:
Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms, and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

These storms may intensify, so be certain to monitor local radio
stations and available television stations for additional information
and possible warnings from the National Weather Service.

properties.description:

mph are expected to develop late tonight and into Friday.
These strong winds will produce waves building to 11 feet.

* TIMING...Late tonight through Friday evening.

* IMPACTS...Minor flooding is likely in flood prone areas along
the Cook and especially Lake and Porter County shorelines in
northwestern Indiana.
properties.instruction:

generate flooding of low areas along the lakeshore.

For information on swim advisories or bans at Chicago beaches
visit: www.cpdbeaches.com.

properties.headline: Special Marine Warning issued April 18 at 11:39AM CDT until April 18 at 12:15PM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
For the following areas...
Calcasieu Lake...
Coastal waters from Cameron LA to High Island TX out 20 NM...
Waters from Cameron LA to High Island TX from 20 to 60 NM...

At 1139 AM CDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing
waterspouts was located 26 nm northeast of Cameron, moving northeast
at 65 knots.

HAZARD...Waterspouts and wind gusts to nearly 50 knots.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Waterspouts can easily overturn boats and create locally
hazardous seas. Small craft could be damaged in briefly
higher winds and suddenly higher waves.

Locations impacted include...
West Cameron Wc303, West Cameron 45, West Cameron 53, High Island
A33, West Cameron 48, West Cameron 149, Sabine Pass 13, West Cameron
398, West Cameron 167, West Cameron 168, High Island 167, High Island
A100, West Cameron 165, High Island A177, West Cameron 342, High
Island A201, West Cameron 130, West Cameron 294, High Island 129 and
High Island 5.
properties.instruction:
A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 700 PM CDT for southwestern
Louisiana...and the adjacent coastal waters.

Thunderstorms can produce sudden waterspouts. Waterspouts can easily
overturn boats and create locally hazardous seas. Seek safe harbor
immediately.

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 18 at 11:34AM CDT until April 18 at 2:30PM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Lake Charles has issued a

* Urban and Small Stream Flood Advisory for...
Central Rapides Parish in central Louisiana...

* Until 230 PM CDT.

* At 1133 AM CDT, Doppler radar indicated heavy rain due to
thunderstorms. This will cause urban and small stream flooding in
the advisory area. Up to two inches of rain have already fallen.

* Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Alexandria, Pineville, Alexandria International Airport, Ball,
Kingsville, Libuse, Tioga, Timber Trails, Poland, Esler Regional
Airport, Kolin and Paradise.

Additional rainfall of One to Two inches are possible over the area.
This additional rain will result in minor flooding.
properties.instruction:

creeks and streams, urban areas, highways, streets and underpasses as
well as other drainage areas and low lying spots.

A Flood Advisory means river or stream flows are elevated, or ponding
of water in urban or other areas is occurring or is imminent.

properties.description:
The Flash Flood Watch remains in effect for

* Portions of Arkansas and Louisiana, including the following
areas, in Arkansas, Columbia and Union. In Louisiana,
Bienville, Caldwell, Claiborne, Grant, Jackson, La Salle,
Lincoln, Natchitoches, Ouachita, Red River, Union, Webster,
and Winn.

* Until 4 PM CDT this afternoon

* Showers and thunderstorms will continue pushing slowly east
across North Central Louisiana. Additional rainfall amounts of
one to two inches possible through the mid afternoon will be
possible before heavy rain diminishes from the west. As a
result, brief localized flash flooding will still be possible.

* Heavy rainfall may lead to flooding of low-lying and poor
drainage areas, as well as flooding of rivers, creeks, and
streams.
properties.instruction:
A Flash Flood Watch means that conditions may develop that lead
to flash flooding. Flash flooding is a very dangerous situation.

You should monitor later forecasts and be prepared to take action
should Flash Flood Warnings be issued.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 18 at 12:32PM EDT by NWS Jackson KY
properties.description:
Very dry conditions of the last couple of days have left leaves,
dead grasses, and dead branches susceptible to burn quickly.
Although the air will not be as dry today, winds will be stronger

spring fire season is ongoing, and more stringent rules
restricting open air burning remain in effect.

properties.headline: Wind Advisory issued April 18 at 11:30AM CDT until April 18 at 6:00PM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
Strong southerly winds will occur over area in response to low
pressure deepening over the southern Plains. Wind speeds exceeding
20 mph...with frequent gusts to 30 mph...can be expected to
linger through the afternoon before diminishing briefly with the
approach of a cold front.
* TIMING...Through the afternoon.


* WINDS...20 to 25 mph with some gusts exceeding 30 mph.

* IMPACTS...Strong southerly winds will make driving difficult
for high profile vehicles along open east-west highways. Small
lawn furniture and garbage cans will be tossed around.
properties.instruction:
A Wind Advisory means that winds of 20 mph are expected. Winds
this strong can make driving difficult, especially for high
profile vehicles. Use extra caution.

NWSheadline: WIND ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM CDT THIS EVENING

The National Weather Service in Lake Charles has issued a

* Small Stream Flood Advisory for...
Eastern Jefferson Davis Parish in southwestern Louisiana...
Acadia Parish in southwestern Louisiana...

Mermentau, Evangeline, Morse, Mowata, Maxie, Mire, Egan, Pine
Island, Thornwell, Branch, Richard, Estherwood and Roanoke.

Additional rainfall of 2 to 4 inches is possible over the area. This
additional rain will result in minor flooding.

properties.areaDesc: Calcasieu Lake; Coastal waters from Cameron LA to High Island TX out 20 NM; Waters from Cameron LA to High Island TX from 20 to 60 NM
properties.headline: Special Marine Warning issued April 18 at 11:20AM CDT until April 18 at 12:15PM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
For the following areas...
Calcasieu Lake...
Coastal waters from Cameron LA to High Island TX out 20 NM...
Waters from Cameron LA to High Island TX from 20 to 60 NM...

At 1120 AM CDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing
waterspouts was located 7 nm north of Cameron, moving northeast at 65
knots.

HAZARD...Waterspouts and wind gusts to nearly 50 knots.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Waterspouts can easily overturn boats and create locally
hazardous seas. Small craft could be damaged in briefly
higher winds and suddenly higher waves.

Locations impacted include...
West Cameron Wc303, West Cameron 45, West Cameron 53, High Island
A33, Sabine Pass 10, High Island 170, West Cameron 48, West Cameron
149, Sabine Pass 13, West Cameron 398, West Cameron 167, West Cameron
168, High Island 167, High Island A100, West Cameron 165, High Island
A177, West Cameron 342, High Island A201, West Cameron 130 and West
Cameron 294.
properties.instruction:
A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 700 PM CDT for southwestern
Louisiana...and the adjacent coastal waters.

Thunderstorms can produce sudden waterspouts. Waterspouts can easily
overturn boats and create locally hazardous seas. Seek safe harbor

properties.instruction:
A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 700 PM CDT for central and
southwestern Louisiana.

For your protection move to an interior room on the lowest floor of a
building.

significant wind damage. Although a tornado is not immediately
likely, it is best to move to an interior room on the lowest floor of
a building. These storms may cause serious injury and significant
property damage.

properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 18 at 11:15AM CDT until April 18 at 11:30AM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
At 1114 AM CDT, a severe squall line capable of producing both
tornadoes and extensive straight line wind damage was located over
Bayou Chicot, or near Turkey Creek, moving east at 30 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

These dangerous storms will be near...
Chicot State Park around 1125 AM CDT.
Bunkie, Indian Lake and Whiteville around 1130 AM CDT.

Other locations impacted by this tornadic thunderstorm include St.
Landry.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to an interior room on the lowest floor of a
sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a mobile
home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter and
protect yourself from flying debris.

properties.headline: Flash Flood Watch issued April 18 at 11:05AM CDT until April 18 at 7:00PM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
Numerous showers and thunderstorms with heavy rainfall rates will
move along a slow moving frontal system for the remainder of the
afternoon. Rainfall amounts will average 1 to 3 inches in a short
period of time, and 4 to 6 inches will be possible where
thunderstorms train or move over the same area for a few hours.
These rainfall amounts will cause the potential for flash
flooding, especially street flooding in poor drainage urban areas.
The flooding hazard will decrease later this afternoon and evening
as the front moves off to the east and thunderstorm activity
decreases.
The National Weather Service in Lake Charles has issued a

* Flash Flood Watch for portions of central Louisiana, south
central Louisiana, and southwest Louisiana, including the
following areas, in central Louisiana, Avoyelles, Evangeline,
Rapides, and St. Landry. In south central Louisiana, Iberia,
Lafayette, Lower St. Martin, St. Mary, and Upper St. Martin.
In southwest Louisiana, Acadia, Allen, East Cameron, Jefferson
Davis, and Vermilion.

* Until 7 PM CDT this evening

* Rainfall amounts 1 to 3 inches with local amounts to 4 to 6
inches possible.

* Flash flooding of urban poor drainage areas and low spots will
be the main concern.
properties.instruction:
A Flash Flood Watch means that conditions may develop that lead
to flash flooding. Flash flooding is a VERY DANGEROUS SITUATION.

You should monitor later forecasts and be prepared to take action
should Flash Flood Warnings be issued.

NWSheadline: FLASH FLOOD WATCH IN EFFECT UNTIL 7 PM CDT THIS EVENING

properties.headline: Air Quality Alert issued April 18 at 8:04AM MST by NWS Phoenix AZ
properties.description:
The Arizona Department of Environmental Quality in Phoenix has issued
an Ozone High Pollution Advisory for the Greater Phoenix Area for
Friday.

This means that forecast weather conditions combined with existing
ozone levels are expected to result in local maximum 8-hour ozone
concentrations that pose a health risk. Adverse health effects
increase as air quality deteriorates.

Ozone is an air contaminant which can cause breathing difficulties
for children as well as persons with respiratory problems. A decrease
in physical activity is recommended.

If it is a regularly scheduled work day, you are urged to car pool,
telecommute or use mass transit.

The use of gasoline-powered equipment should be reduced or done late
in the day.

For details on this High Pollution Advisory for Maricopa County,
visit the ADEQ internet site at www.azdeq.gov or call 602-771-2300.

NWSheadline: HIGH POLLUTION ADVISORY FOR MARICOPA COUNTY INCLUDING THE GREATER PHOENIX AREA FRIDAY

Service.

properties.areaDesc: Lake Pontchartrain and Lake Maurepas; Lake Borgne
properties.headline: Gale Warning issued April 18 at 10:40AM CDT until April 19 at 10:00AM CDT by NWS New Orleans LA
properties.description:
A vigorous spring storm developing in the lower Plains States
will move through the Mississippi Valley Thursday. The surface
low associated with this system will deepen considerably today.
Onshore flow will be increasing from west to east through the
morning, spreading eastward this afternoon and evening. A cold
front will then move through overnight leading to a strong wind
shift and winds quickly ramping back up. Winds will ease some
Friday with small craft conditions taking back over before winds
finally fall below advisory criteria Saturday.
* WINDS...Southeast winds 20 to 30 knots with higher gusts, then
northwest 25 to 30 knots gusts to 40 knots Thursday evening
and night, diminishing to 20 knots and gusty Friday through
Saturday morning.

* WAVES/SEAS...3 to 5 feet occasional 8 feet, becoming mixed
seas Thursday night, then 4 to 6 feet near shore, 8 to 12 feet
occasional 15 feet well offshore.
properties.instruction:
A Small Craft Advisory means that wind speeds of 20 to 33 knots
are expected to produce hazardous wave conditions to small craft.
Inexperienced mariners...especially those operating smaller
vessels should avoid navigating in these conditions.

A Gale Warning means winds of 34 to 47 knots are imminent or
occuring. Operating a vessel in gale conditions requires
experience and properly equipped vessels. It is highly
recommended that mariners without the proper experience seek safe
harbor prior to the onset of gale conditions.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 18 at 10:08AM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
At 1008 AM CDT, Doppler radar was tracking a strong thunderstorm over
Rockefeller Wildlife Range, moving northeast at 55 mph.

Wind gusts up to 50 mph will be possible with this storm.

Locations impacted include...
Lafayette, Crowley, Abbeville, Kaplan, Gueydan, Rockefeller Wildlife
Range, Forked Island, Grand Chenier, Klondike, Maurice, Morse,
Riceville, Meaux, Wright, Indian Bayou, Lyons Point, Estherwood,
Florence Landing and Midland.
properties.instruction:
Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

This storm may intensify, so be certain to monitor local radio
stations and available television stations for additional information
and possible warnings from the National Weather Service.

properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

Do not drive through flowing water. Nearly half of all flood
fatalities are vehicle related. As little as 6 inches of water may
cause you to lose control of your vehicle. Two feet of water will
carry most vehicles away.This product along with additional weather
and stream information is available at www.weather.gov/kc/.

properties.headline: Small Craft Advisory issued April 18 at 10:03AM CDT until April 19 at 7:00AM CDT by NWS Brownsville TX
properties.description:
The cold front has moved east of the lower Texas coast this
morning, with light to moderate winds expected into this
afternoon. A secondary surge of northwest winds is expected to
arrive around sunset this evening and continue through late tonight.
This surge will bring northwest winds reaching 25 knots through
the overnight hours, and will increase seas to 7 to 10 feet across
the Gulf. Conditions are expected to improve quickly on Friday.
* WINDS...Northwest 20 to 25 knots, with frequent gusts of 30
knots across Gulf of Mexico waters.

* BAY CONDITIONS...Rough bay waters.

* GULF SEAS...7 to 10 feet.
properties.instruction:
A Small Craft Advisory means that wind speeds of 20 to 33 knots
are expected to produce hazardous wave conditions to small craft.
Inexperienced mariners...especially those operating smaller
vessels should avoid navigating in these conditions.

NWSheadline: SMALL CRAFT ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT FROM 7 PM CDT THIS EVENING TO 7 AM CDT FRIDAY

occurring. Operating a vessel in gale conditions requires

harbor prior to the onset of gale conditions.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 18 at 10:56AM EDT until April 21 at 8:00PM EDT by NWS Marquette MI
properties.description:
Paint River at Crystal Falls affecting Iron County
The National Weather Service in Marquette has issued a
* Flood Warning for
The Paint River at Crystal Falls.
* from this evening to Sunday evening.
* At 7:00 AM Thursday the stage was 6.0 feet.
* Flood stage is 7.0 feet.
* Minor flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...Rise above flood stage by late this afternoon and
continue to rise to near 7.5 feet by tomorrow morning. The river
will fall below flood stage by Saturday evening.
* At 7.0 feet...Waterfront park areas near the M-69 bridge and
low-lying areas along the river in Crystal Falls become
inundated.
* At 5.5 feet...River exceeds bankfull stage.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

Safety message...Even 6 inches of fast moving flood water can knock
you off your feet...and a depth of 2 feet will float your car. Never
try to walk...swim...or drive through such swift water. If you come
upon flood waters...stop...turn around and go another way.

Additional weather and river information is available at
www.weather.gov/mqt

properties.headline: Special Marine Warning issued April 18 at 9:55AM CDT until April 18 at 10:30AM CDT by NWS Lake Charles LA
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Lake Charles has issued a

* Special Marine Warning for...
Coastal waters from Intracoastal City to Cameron LA out 20 NM...
Coastal waters from Lower Atchafalaya River to Intracoastal City LA
out 20 NM...
Vermilion Bay...

* Until 1030 AM CDT.

* At 955 AM CDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing
waterspouts was located over South Marsh Island 217, or 13 nm
southwest of Marsh Island, moving northeast at 65 knots.

HAZARD...Waterspouts and wind gusts to 40 knots.

SOURCE...Radar.

IMPACT...Waterspouts can easily overturn boats and create locally
hazardous seas. Small craft could be damaged in briefly
higher winds and suddenly higher waves.

* Locations impacted include...
South Marsh Island 217, Vermilion 31 and West Cote Blanche Bay.
properties.instruction:
Thunderstorms can produce sudden waterspouts. Waterspouts can easily
overturn boats and create locally hazardous seas. Seek safe harbor
immediately.
